library(dplyr)

data = data %>% mutate(doc_id = row_number())

Text Preprocessing

For the next analysis we need to preprocess our data. We need to tokenize to divide tweets into words as we analyse them separately (for now), it is crucial to lemmatize words to leave only initial form of the word that will simplify the process, deleting stop words is needed to delete the most frequent words that do not make any sense (for example, “the”, “a” and so on), and finally deleting of punctuation and digits is needed because they can disturb our analysis

library(textstem)
library(tidytext)
library(stopwords)

data$OriginalTweet = iconv(data$OriginalTweet, "UTF-8", "UTF-8", sub=' ')

data_lemmas = data %>%
    unnest_tokens(word, OriginalTweet, token="tweets") %>%
    mutate(lem = lemmatize_words(word)) %>%
    filter(! lem %in% stopwords("en")) %>%
    filter(! str_detect(lem, "[0-9]+")) 

head(data_lemmas)

We can see that everything works good!

Contrastive analysis

library(tidyr)
pos_words = data_lemmas %>% filter(Senti == "Positive") %>% mutate(sentim = "pos")
neg_words = data_lemmas %>% filter(Senti == "Negative") %>% mutate(sentim = "neg")

tweets.lemmas = bind_rows(pos_words, neg_words) %>%
    dplyr::count(lem, sentim) %>%
    spread(sentim, n, fill = 0) %>%
    dplyr::filter(pos > 10 | neg > 10)

head(tweets.lemmas)

Here we can see the number of the the most frequent words among positive and negative words. We can notice that some words are more frequently used in positive sense while others in negative.

Let’s calculate Dunning log-likelihood (G^2) to see whether words are statistically significantly different between two groups

Function itself:

g2 = function(a, b) {
  c = sum(a)
  d = sum(b)
  E1 = c * ((a + b) / (c + d))
  E2 = d * ((a + b) / (c + d))
  return(2*((a*log(a/E1+1e-7)) + (b*log(b/E2+1e-7))))
}

Calculating:

tweets.g2 = tweets.lemmas %>% 
    mutate(g2=g2(pos, neg)) %>%
    arrange(desc(g2)) %>%
    mutate(g2 = round(g2, 2))

head(tweets.g2)

We can see that, for example, word “panic” is more frequently used in negative tweets and the difference with positive tweets is huge.

Now let’s proceed to effect size to see for which group words are commonly used. For this purpose we will calculate log-ratio

Function itself:

logratio = function(a, b) {
    return(log2((a/sum(a)/(b/sum(b)))))
}

Calculating:

tweets.lr = tweets.g2 %>%
    mutate(logodds = logratio(pos, neg))

Let’s make a visualisation of the obtained results to see the most different words for positive and negative words

library(ggplot2)
tweets.lr %>%
    filter(pos > 0 & neg > 0) %>%
    group_by(logodds < 0) %>%
    top_n(15, abs(logodds)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    mutate(lem = reorder(lem, logodds)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(lem, logodds, fill = logodds < 0)) +
    geom_col(show.legend = TRUE) +
    coord_flip() +
    ylab("Log odds ratio") +
    scale_fill_discrete(name = "", labels = c("Positive", "Negative"))

We can see dramatic differences between negative and positive tweets: there are even mentions of diseases in negative tweets. Moreover, “wtf” just describes the general attitude about COVID-19 for all people who tweeted negatively, I guess…

Preparing data for the classification

Creating document-term matrix

We will start with counting lemmas in each tweet

lem_count = data_lemmas%>% count(lem, doc_id, sort=TRUE)
head(lem_count, 10)

Calculating TF-IDF:

tfidf = lem_count %>%
    bind_tf_idf(lem, doc_id, n)
head(tfidf)

Here we can see how important each word to each document in a collection or corpus.

Now let’s build doc-term matrix and filter data a little. Each word should appear at least 1 time and at least in 0.5 % of docs

library(quanteda)
dfm = tfidf %>%
    filter(tf_idf>0) %>%
    cast_dfm(doc_id, lem, n) %>% 
    dfm_trim(min_termfreq=1, termfreq_type="count") %>% 
    dfm_trim(min_docfreq=0.005, docfreq_type="prop") %>% 
    dfm_tfidf

dfm_count = tfidf %>%
    filter(tf_idf>0) %>%
    cast_dfm(doc_id, lem, n) %>% 
    dfm_trim(min_termfreq=1, termfreq_type="count") %>% 
    dfm_trim(min_docfreq=0.005, docfreq_type="prop")

nrow(dfm_count)
## [1] 33441
ncol(dfm_count)
## [1] 595

In the final document term matrix we have 33441 (rows) x 595 (columns). Columns are the features that are the basis for machine learning algorithms in predictions.

Splitting the data into train and test sets

As for now let’s split our data into train and test tests. Here we will need doc_id because in dfm matrix doc ids are shuffled, so we select target classes according the order of doc ids in dfm matrix

Here is our target variable:

sentiment_labels = data$Senti[as.integer(rownames(dfm_count))]

The splitting itself:

library(caret)
set.seed(1991)
split = createDataPartition(y=sentiment_labels, p = 0.9, list = FALSE)
train.data = dfm_count %>% dfm_subset(rownames(dfm) %in% rownames(dfm_count)[split])
test.data = dfm_count %>% dfm_subset(!rownames(dfm) %in% rownames(dfm_count)[split]) 

response = as.factor(sentiment_labels)
trainY = response[split]
testY = response[-split]

As Naive Bayes can only use the words that appear in train set during the prediction we will restrict the vocabulary of test set with the words that appear in train set:

test.matched = test.data %>% 
    dfm_match(features = featnames(train.data))

What about the size of the sets?

nrow(test.data)
## [1] 3343
nrow(train.data)
## [1] 30098

We have 3343 observations in test data and 30098 observations in training data.

Building classification model and evaluating model performance

Metric

We should consider Recall as the main metric of our model estimation because we should care about False Negative results. It is crucial for this particular classification task to avoid situations when negative tweets are predicted as positive ones.

(We have an inverted situation with classes compared to this picture: positive became negative, and negative became positive):

Let’s train Naive Bayes model on training data.

Logistic Regression

The main idea of logistic regression is to predict class of target variable using probabilities by having the log-odds. It is similar to Naive Bayes algorithm as it also deals with probabilities but the calculations are different.

Preprocessing

Before we start we need to make some data manipulations

#splitting the data
library(rsample)
set.seed(1991)
tweets_split = data %>%
  select(doc_id) %>%
  initial_split()
train_data_glm = training(tweets_split)
test_data_glm = testing(tweets_split)


#tidy data 
tidy_data = data %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, OriginalTweet, token="tweets") %>% 
  group_by(word) %>%
  filter(n() > 10) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(word = lemmatize_words(word)) %>%
  filter(! word %in% stopwords("en")) %>%
  filter(! str_detect(word, "[0-9]+")) 

#sparsing
sparse_words = tidy_data %>%
  count(doc_id, word) %>%
  inner_join(train_data_glm) %>%
  cast_sparse(doc_id, word, n)

#joining
word_rownames = as.integer(rownames(sparse_words))
tweets_joined = data_frame(doc_id = word_rownames) %>%
  left_join(data %>%
    select(doc_id, Senti))

For classification with logistic regression we will use function cv.glmnet that already includes cross-validation so we need only to specify our training data.

library(glmnet)

is_pos = tweets_joined$Senti == "Positive"
model.glm = cv.glmnet(sparse_words, is_pos,
  family = "binomial",
  keep = TRUE, 
  nfolds = 10
)

summary(model.glm)

Summary of this model does not tell any story so let’s proceed to analysis of predictors

Analysis of predictors

We can derive predictors from our model and see what predictors are the most important.

library(broom)
coefs = model.glm$glmnet.fit %>%
  tidy() %>%
  filter(lambda == model.glm$lambda.1se)

library(tidyverse)

coefs %>%
  group_by(estimate > 0) %>%
  top_n(10, abs(estimate)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot(aes(fct_reorder(term, estimate), estimate, fill = estimate > 0)) +
  geom_col(alpha = 0.8, show.legend = TRUE) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    x = NULL,
    title = "Coefficients that increase/decrease probability the most"
  )

We can notice that we have some similarities in the results of predictors analysis: semantically (by meaning of the words) they are similar. We can even see our lovely “wtf” and “scam”. In general, we can track similar trend of predictors, so it means that we have good models

Testing on test data

To test our model on test data we need to pull out the intercept of prediction from the coefficients dataframe and combine with sum of estimates for each word

intercept = coefs %>%
  filter(term == "(Intercept)") %>%
  pull(estimate)

classifications = tidy_data %>%
  inner_join(test_data_glm) %>%
  inner_join(coefs, by = c("word" = "term")) %>%
  group_by(doc_id) %>%
  summarize(score = sum(estimate)) %>%
  mutate(probability = plogis(intercept + score))

head(classifications)

We can see that we obtained the probabilities of tweets to be positive or negative. Now let’s take a look at ROC curve that helps to understand the model performance evaluation.

library(yardstick)

comment_classes = classifications %>%
  left_join(data %>%
    select(Senti, doc_id), by = "doc_id") %>%
  mutate(Senti = as.factor(Senti))

comment_classes %>%
  roc_curve(Senti, probability, event_level = "second") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = 1 - specificity, y = sensitivity)) +
  geom_line(
    color = "midnightblue",
    size = 1.5
  ) +
  geom_abline(
    lty = 2, alpha = 0.5,
    color = "gray50",
    size = 1.2
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "ROC curve for tweets classification",
    subtitle = "Predicting whether tweet is positive or negative"
  )

This plot shows us how the sensitivity and specificity are interconnected in our model. We are more interested in Area Under Curve (AUC) that is easier for interpretation of model performance evaluation.

comment_classes %>%
  roc_auc(Senti, probability, event_level = "second")

We can see pretty good results! It means that logistic regression works well for tweets classification.

Comparison with Naive Bayes

To compare these results with results from Naive Bayes we can create confusion matrix.

comment_classes %>%
  mutate(
    prediction = case_when(
      probability > 0.5 ~ "Positive",
      TRUE ~ "Negative"
    ),
    prediction = as.factor(prediction)
  ) %>%
  conf_mat(Senti, prediction)
##           Truth
## Prediction Negative Positive
##   Negative     3385      469
##   Positive      505     3994

Don’t worry that we have more results in this data. We just have a split 80/20. We can still count the Recall

3385/(3385+505)
## [1] 0.8701799

We can see that we have much better Recall compared to Naive Bayes where we have 0.75 (0.87 > 0.75). We can assume that logistic regression works much better for tweets classification in comparison with Naive Bayes.
